# FE ↔ BE Mappings (TypeScript/JavaScript to Java/Spring)

## Core keyword mapping

- `const x = ...` (TS/JS) ↔ `final Type x = ...` (Java local variable or field)
- `readonly prop: T` (TS class field) ↔ `final` field in Java class
- `static` (TS/JS) ↔ `static` (Java)

## Mental model

- `final` in Java means the reference can be assigned only once.
- This is similar to `const` in JS/TS: no rebinding, but the object can still be mutable.

## Mutability example

TypeScript / JavaScript:

```ts
const user = { name: "A" };
user.name = "B"; // ✅ allowed
// user = { name: "C" }; // ❌ not allowed
```

Java:

```java
final User user = new User("A");
user.setName("B"); // ✅ allowed
// user = new User("C"); // ❌ not allowed
```

## Class field mapping

TypeScript:

```ts
class A {
  readonly repo: Repo;
  constructor(repo: Repo) {
    this.repo = repo;
  }
}
```

Java:

```java
class A {
  private final Repo repo;

  public A(Repo repo) {
    this.repo = repo;
  }
}
```

## Java-only `final` uses

- `final` method: cannot be overridden in subclasses.
- `final` class: cannot be extended.
- `final` parameter: cannot be reassigned inside method body.

## In this project

In `TaskService`, this line:

```java
private final TaskRepository taskRepository;
```

means Spring injects the dependency once in the constructor, and the reference cannot later point to a different repository instance.
